The Economics of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly in the news, and therefore many would probably say war.
But this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions to this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would gladly end every war and violence, just as we would gladly put an end to poverty, hunger, and global warming, and provide all people with access to education.
Yet, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities, and for this one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals, in their view, would be the most sensible.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of means that would otherwise flow, for example, into the fight against hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at the University of Oxford, violence in society—murders and especially violence against women and children—poses a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die as a result of interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries report murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization refers to as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a person's life and society $9.1 million.
Measured against the global GDP, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GSP).
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the global economy, but rather a way of expressing the consequences.
If murder were abolished, societies around the world would be better off in a way that could be measured by 1.7% of GDP.
Let's compare this with the distinctly lower costs of civil wars, which correspond to about 0.2% of global GDP.
That is still far less than the largest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, forced into marriage at a young age, exposed to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and subjected to genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by partners amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars, or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of child abuse varies from culture to culture, but roughly 15% of children experience each month what the UN refers to as severe physical punishment.
This includes hitting the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are hit repeatedly and as violently as possible with an object.
This suffering befalls about 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of the global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid funds is currently flowing into the reduction of violence in society and the improvement of criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals scream out for something to be done.
Unfortunately, there are still hardly any secure insights into where the limited resources should best be applied.
Everything that can be said is that the money spent to reduce violence could be used more effectively.
Large sums of aid money are designated for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects that include the component of "crime prevention."
Other programs may contribute indirectly, but it's obviously possible to do much better.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the U.S. state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and reduce the costs of child welfare services and legal expenses.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 US dollars: it is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program called SASA! is working in Uganda.
(Kisuaheli for "Now!") has promoted the view that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
That is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost efficiency available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach—including a time limit for alcohol sales, the reclaiming of public space, and improvements in the police and justice system—the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
That is still a high number, but much lower than the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 residents in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and insights from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of significant importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on the more effective enforcement of existing regulations showed that physical assaults could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We may still not know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children brings costs of 8 billion US dollars per year to society, thus representing a massive – and far too little noticed – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
For this reason, the reduction of domestic violence is among the top priorities for the next development goals of the world.
